\begin_layout Section
Model of Computation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The computational cost in this paper is analysed by bounding the number
 of arithmetic operations (additions, subtractions, multiplications, and
 divisions) in the coefficient field 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{K}$
\end_inset

 on an algebraic random access machine.
 We use 
\begin_inset Formula $\MM(n,d)$
\end_inset

 to denote the cost of multiplying two polynomial matrices with dimension
 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 and degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\M(n)$
\end_inset

 to denote the cost of multiplying two polynomials with degree 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 We define a cost function 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\M}(d)=d\log d\log\log d$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\M}(ab)\in O\left(\bar{\M}(a)\bar{\M}(b)\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\M}(n)\in O(n^{\omega-1})$
\end_inset

.
 We take 
\begin_inset Formula $\MM(n,d)\in O\left(n^{\omega}\M(d)\right)\subset O(n^{\omega}\bar{\M}(d))$
\end_inset

, where the multiplication exponent 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is assumed to satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $2<\omega\le3$
\end_inset

.
 We refer to the book by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vonzurgathen"

\end_inset

 for more details and reference about the cost of polynomial multiplication
 and matrix multiplication.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Shifted Degrees
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:columnDegreesRowDegreesSymmetry"

\end_inset

A matrix
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\in\mathbb{K}\left[x\right]^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

-column degrees bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

 if and only if its 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{v}$
\end_inset

-row degrees are bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{u}$
\end_inset

.
 In addition, for a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

-column degrees 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

, it has a full-rank leading 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

-column coefficient matrix if and only if it has a full-rank leading 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{v}$
\end_inset

-row coefficient matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The lemma follows from the fact 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\vec{u}}\mathbf{A}x^{-\vec{v}}$
\end_inset

 has degree bounded by 0 (Note that the negative degrees are define here
 by setting
\begin_inset Formula $\deg x^{-d}=-d$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $d\in\mathbb{Z}_{>0}$
\end_inset

.
 If one wishes to avoid this negative degrees, one can simply shift the
 degrees up by multiplying the matrix by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{a}$
\end_inset

 for some large 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

).
 Note the symmetry between the shifted row degrees and the shifted column
 degrees.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:productDegreeBound"

\end_inset

If the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

-column degrees of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\in\mathbb{K}\left[x\right]^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

 are bounded by the corresponding entries of an integer list 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}\in\mathbb{Z}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}$
\end_inset

-column degrees of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}\in\mathbb{K}\left[x\right]^{n\times k}$
\end_inset

 are bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{w}\in\mathbb{Z}^{k}$
\end_inset

, then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

-column degrees of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 are bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{w}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\vec{u}}\mathbf{A}x^{-\vec{v}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\vec{v}}\mathbf{B}^{-\vec{w}}$
\end_inset

 have degrees bounded by 0.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\vec{u}}\mathbf{A}x^{-\vec{v}}x^{\vec{v}}\mathbf{B}^{-\vec{w}}=x^{\vec{u}}\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}^{-\vec{w}}$
\end_inset

 also has degree bounded by 0, or equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdeg_{\vec{u}}\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}\le\vec{w}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:productDegreeBoundWithRowDegrees"

\end_inset

If the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

-row degrees of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\in\mathbb{K}\left[x\right]^{m\times n}$
\end_inset

 are bounded by the corresponding entries of an integer list 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}\in\mathbb{Z}^{n}$
\end_inset

, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{u}$
\end_inset

-column degrees of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{B}\in\mathbb{K}\left[x\right]^{n\times k}$
\end_inset

 are bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{w}\in\mathbb{Z}^{k}$
\end_inset

, then the 
\begin_inset Formula $-\vec{v}$
\end_inset

-column degrees of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}$
\end_inset

 are bounded by 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{w}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-\vec{v}}\mathbf{A}x^{\vec{u}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-\vec{u}}\mathbf{B}^{-\vec{w}}$
\end_inset

 have degrees bounded by 0.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{-\vec{v}}\mathbf{A}x^{\vec{u}}x^{-\vec{u}}\mathbf{B}^{-\vec{w}}=x^{-\vec{v}}\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}^{-\vec{w}}$
\end_inset

 also has degree bounded by 0, or equivalently, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdeg_{-\vec{v}}\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}\le\vec{w}$
\end_inset

.
 Alternatively, this also follows from the fact 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdeg_{-\vec{v}}\mathbf{A}\le-\vec{u}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "lem:productDegreeBound"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following lemma is known as the predictable-degree property
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "kailath:1980"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:predictableDegree"

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 is a full-rank 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

-column reduced matrix with 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdeg_{\vec{u}}\mathbf{A}=\vec{v}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdeg_{\vec{v}}\mathbf{B}=\vec{w}$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdeg_{\vec{u}}\left(\mathbf{A}\mathbf{B}\right)=\vec{w}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{u}$
\end_inset

-column reduced means the leading column coefficient matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 of 
